<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,258,859]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,258,283]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: Color on back brownish gray and brownish yellow on the ventral side, fur is coarse with soft underwool (
<figureCitation box="[158,257,294,319]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,2001,2023]" captionTargetBox="[391,1203,903,1986]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[391,1203,903,1986]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. The Persian squirrel, Sciurus anomalusin Dibbīn Forest Reserve (photo RSCN)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202789/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Figure 5</figureCitation>
). Tail thick, bushy and flattened in appearance. Ears with very short tufts. Muzzle short and blunt. Eyes surrounded by yellowish hair. Thumbs of forefeet vestigial. Hind feet with 5 digits. Dorsal side of tail is light redbrownish. Five pairs of mammae. Strong depression of the braincase posteriorly. Postorbital process of frontal present and distinctively sharp pointed. Low molar crowns and square-like shaped (
<figureCitation box="[1087,1185,402,427]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,2003,2025]" captionTargetBox="[380,1223,195,1975]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[355,1239,187,1986]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. A.Dorsal, B. Ventral, C. Lateral views of the skull, and D. Mandible for Sciurus anomalus. Scale bar = 10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202791/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Figure 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,258,859]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,438,463]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Localities</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[331,541,438,463]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Previous records.</emphasis>
Kufrinja (
<bibRefCitation box="[661,877,438,463]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" refId="ref31125" refString="Amr, Z. S. &amp; Disi, A. M. (1988) Jordanian Mammals Acquired by the Jordan University Natural History Museum. Publication of the University of Jordan, Amman, 32 pp." type="book">Amr &amp; Disi, 1988</bibRefCitation>
); Burmā (Harrison &amp; Bates, 1991); Ajlūn Forest Reserve, Dibbīn Forest Reserve, Rimon, between Sakib and ‘Anjara (
<bibRefCitation box="[956,1156,474,499]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" refId="ref31068" refString="Amr, Z., Eid, E., Qarqaz, M. A. &amp; Abu Baker, M. (2006) The status and distribution of the Persian Squirrel, Sciurus anomalus, in Dibbeen Nature Reserve. Zoologische Abhandlungen (Dresden), 55 (1), 9 - 17." type="journal article">
Amr 
<emphasis box="[1019,1071,474,499]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">et al</emphasis>
., 2006
</bibRefCitation>
); Ajlūn (AUB specimen cited in Atallah, 1978). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[417,566,510,535]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">New records</emphasis>
. Tabaqat Fahl (
<figureCitation box="[739,837,510,535]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1423,1445]" captionTargetBox="[275,1307,228,1369]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[264,1323,193,1402]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Distribution of the Persian squirrel, Sciurus anomalus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202793/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Figure 7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,258,859]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,300,546,571]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Habitat:</emphasis>
It is associated with thick pine and oak forests in northern Jordan. 
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="1835976058" country="Jordan" location="Dibbeen Forest" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Ajlun">
Locally, the Persian squirrel is uncommon and hard to spot in the mountains of 
<collectingRegion box="[742,809,582,607]" country="Jordan" name="Ajlun" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Ajlūn</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[826,896,582,607]" country="Jordan" name="Jarash" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Jarash</collectingRegion>
and Ishtafayna where pine and oak trees are abundant. It uses tree holes as nests and can be located using the piles of eaten acorns and cones under trees. In a recent study, the presence of the Persian squirrel, 
<emphasis box="[705,912,654,679]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Guldenstaedt" authorityYear="1785" box="[705,908,654,679]" class="Mammalia" family="Sciuridae" genus="Sciurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="anomalus">Sciurus anomalus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
was confirmed in 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:C32887CBFF97BA6AFF3DFF60FB4EED9B:4E5E6006FF97BA64FBCAFD79FAE1E884" box="[1120,1292,654,679]" country="Jordan" name="Dibbeen Forest" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" stateProvince="Ajlun">Dibbeen Forest</location>
Reserve and other localities in 
<collectingCountry box="[356,434,690,715]" name="Jordan" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Jordan</collectingCountry>
. The records were based on direct visual observations and finding remains of consumed pine cones. Examination of freshly consumed pine-cone remains constituted an excellent tool to record the presence and distribution of squirrels across the reserve. Freshly consumed pinecones formed continuous clusters in most of the studied localities. Also, remains of fresh, old and very old pine cones were concentrated in pine forested areas, and with less frequency in mixed pine-oak forested regions (
<bibRefCitation box="[996,1187,834,859]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" refId="ref31068" refString="Amr, Z., Eid, E., Qarqaz, M. A. &amp; Abu Baker, M. (2006) The status and distribution of the Persian Squirrel, Sciurus anomalus, in Dibbeen Nature Reserve. Zoologische Abhandlungen (Dresden), 55 (1), 9 - 17." type="journal article">
Amr 
<emphasis box="[1057,1105,834,859]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">et al</emphasis>
., 2006
</bibRefCitation>
).
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
